When the food arrived, all of our plates came with French fries despite none of us ordering French fries. When the waiter came over he said they had run out of potatoes. So I was unable to get mashed potatoes and my friend was unable to get potatoes gratin. I was even more upset because the couple next to us had the same exact meal with mashed potatoes so they technically got our meal first. I don’t understand why the waiter did not inform us of them running out my mashed potatoes and instead filled our plates with French fries that none of us ordered. The waiter then offered us free drinks and allowed me to choose another meal. I chose the seafood which took another 45 minutes. I had to watch my friends eat their food while I sat at the table waiting. The pasta did not have a pleasant taste at all and the noodles were overcooked. I did not finish the meal at all. TLDR: Authentic Harlem experience with great food, good prices on drinks, and casual service. A regular spot for me.  I've lived in the neighborhood about 5 years, and took far too long to really give this place a chance. I've been frequenting RDV (Rendezvous) and Harlem Food Bar as my regular spots. Recently, they both have been open far less for lunch during the day, and I found myself going here.  In the past three weeks, I have probably been here about 5ish times. Three times for dinner and twice for lunch. The food has been consistently great, and the drinks are well priced (mind you, I have only drank wine here!).  Sometimes, you may get somewhat slower service at first, or there is a lot of internal activity like vendors, and inventorying, happening right in the front (the bar area). I actually have come to find it somewhat authentic and a refreshing flavor of Harlem dining. We're not going for white tablecloth here people. Once your orders are in, things are speedy and delicious. It is my current go to spot in the neighborhood and they have some of the most flexible hours for eating of anywhere in Harlem.  The Coq Au Vin is slightly non-traditional (includes Linguine) but is fantastic. The duck is perfect. Chicken Paillard is what you'd expect. Sides are good so definitely give them a go!

What a great first time dining experience! We didn't have any reservations but we still tried. Lucky for us, we got seated quickly on a Saturday evening.  The vibe was really chill. Great for a dinner date and drinks or with a group of friends.  The truffle mac and cheese whetted our appetite. It smelled really good. It was sublime.  I ordered the Demi Poulet because I saw the other table being served and the scent just wafted to our table and I just had to have it. Great choice! It was very tender, juicy, and seasoned well.  My Bub’s New York shell steak was cooked Medium Rare. He complimented how the crust outside was perfect!  The serving portions were just right for the price and quality. You won't feel short-changed.  Service was pleasant and quick! Our server was very affable.  Worth trying their brunch menu next time!

This used to be one of my wife's and my's favorite restaurants.  Unfortunately, this place has really slipped - especially on the service front - over the past year.  We went to Maison Harlem just last night after having avoided it for close to six months due to bad service.  Whelp, yet again this past evening the service was very disappointing.  I ordered a burger and my wife ordered the sliders.  After about 30 minutes of waiting for our food we asked our waiter if he could check on our meals for us.  Mind you, the restaurant was only about half full.  About ten minutes after that our food finally arrived.  However they brought out a burger as opposed the sliders that my wife had ordered.  The waiter at first tried to make it seem as though it was our fault -as  though we didn't order the sliders.  I reminded the waiter that my wife specifically asked what was on the sliders while ordering them.  After now waiting an additional ten minutes for the sliders i asked the waiter how much longer it would take and his comment was "just as few more minutes - if you'd like you can cancel the order."???  I told him "no" and that we'd just like our food.  Shortly after that the sliders appeared.  Then when the bill came - the sliders were on the bill???  We called over another waiter to ask why the sliders were on the bill when we waited 45 minutes for them.  This waiter asked if we'd like them taken off the bill - which of course we had them do.  Not once did either waiter apologize for the slow service or bringing out the wrong meal.  Neither did they ask if we'd like something to tied us over until our food arrived.  All we got was attitude for not being thrilled with the slow service and the wrong meal having been brought out.  It goes without saying: we will not go back to Maison Harlem.

I never write reviews, but this has happened the past 3 or 4 times that I've attempted to enjoy Maison and I find it a bit irritating at this point. The bartender(s) seem to be more interested in socializing with friends that have popped in to visit them as opposed to asking what the actual *paying* customer who walks into the establishment may want. It's doubly bad after you've been waiting to place an order and then the individual who walks in 10 minutes *after* you is immediately asked what they would like to order etc, etc... (was quite clear that I came in to order something, as I was sitting there with card & ID in hand). As long time RE broker in the area, it's difficult to recommend the establishment to clients when this is the type of service received repeatedly recently. Was going to have lunch & wine, ended up walking out. Will try again in the future (at some point) but this can't be happening regularly (best case, at all) because people won't want to come back.
